<DOC><DOCNO> AP880828-0023 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 1135EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-Germany-PlaneCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0669 08-28 0270</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Germany-Plane Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0669,0270</SECOND><HEAD>URGENT</HEAD><HEAD>Two Jets Crash At Air Show; Up To 100 Spectators Injured</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with official saying one plane crasheddirectly into crowd, deaths likely, radio report that 100 injured,including 15 with serious burns, more on planes. No pickup.</NOTE><DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Italian air force jetscollided during an air show at a U.S. military base Sunday beforeplunging to the ground and injuring up to 100 spectators, anofficial and news reports said.   A U.S. Air Force colonel at Ramstein Air Base told TheAssociated Press that ``anywhere from 20 to 100'' people were hurtamong several hundred people who turned out to watch thedemonstration.   Hesse State radio in Frankfurt also said up to 100 spectatorswere injured, including about 15 who received ``serious burns.''   ``We have to assume there will be some deaths,'' said BerndNagel, a spokesman for Rhineland Palatinate state, where theRamstein base is located.   The planes collided in the air, then crashed into the crowd ofspectators at the Ramstein base in southwestern Germany, thecolonel said. He said there was an unconfirmed report that a thirdairplane was involved in the crash.   Nagel said eyewitnesses reported that one of the planes ploweddirectly into the crowd of spectators. Police in nearbyKaiserlautern said the two falling jets and debris from them``crashed into the crowd.''   The colonel, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the twoplanes belonged to a 10-airplane Italian air force demonstrationteam. Other officials said the planes belonged to the ``FrecceTricolori'' flying team.</TEXT></DOC>